category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to take a string of characters and make it run backwards.</p>
discussion=<p>This custom function is called with a statement such as one of the following:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">get</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> reversed(&quot;A man, a canal, Panama&quot;)</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> reversed(it) into field &quot;Reversed Text&quot;</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">answer</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> reversed(field &quot;Answer&quot;)</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The &quot;reversed&quot; function reverses whatever string is passed to it, character by character, so that the string it returns is the &quot;backwards&quot; version of the original string.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The handler uses a <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> control structure to scan each character in the string. Unlike a typical repeat loop, this one doesn't start at the first character and go to the last. Instead, it uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font>...<font face="Courier" size="11">down to</font> form to start at the last character and go back to the first.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The handler places each character at the end of a variable called &quot;reversedString&quot;. Because the repeat loop in this handler goes backwards, the &quot;reversedString&quot; variable ends up holding the same characters as the original string, but in reverse order. When the repeat loop finishes, the &quot;reversedString&quot; variable is returned as the value of the function.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You can use similar handlers to reverse the words or lines in a string. In fact, using the <font face="Courier" size="11">itemDelimiter</font> property, you can reverse the items in a string, using any character as the item delimiter.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>A note on efficiency:</b></font></p>\n<p>You might initially think that using the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat for each form</font> of the repeat control structure would be faster, since in general, this form takes much less time than the repeat with x = firstValue to lastValue form:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">repeat</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">for</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> each character thisChar in theString</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> thisChar before reversedString</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">repeat</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>However, this turns out to be slower in this particular case. The reason is that it takes longer to put a string before a variable than to put a string after a variable. Since we need to reverse the string, and since the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat for each</font> form doesn't have a way to go backwards, we have no choice but to put each character before the &quot;reversedString&quot; variable. The speed loss from doing this is much greater for this handler than the speed we'd gain from using the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat for each</font> form.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Reversing text
solution=<p><font color="#0000FF">function</font> reversed theString</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">repeat</font> <font color="#980517">with</font> thisChar = the <font color="#F88017">length</font> of theString down to 1</p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">put</font> char thisChar of theString after reversedString</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">end</font> <font color="#980517">repeat</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">return</font> reversedString</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> reversed</p>
title=Reversing text